00:19:13.079 --> 00:19:14.520
Okay, one more time.

00:19:15.880 --> 00:19:16.439
One more.

00:19:17.400 --> 00:19:21.400
Hey, so yeah, so lots of noise during the optimization.

00:19:21.400 --> 00:19:23.000
You can see a little bit of moving around.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:24.040
Not that much.

00:19:24.040 --> 00:19:26.520
I was surprised that it wasn't moving that much.

00:19:26.520 --> 00:19:30.280
When you visualize t-SNE, which I probably should have included as well.

00:19:30.280 --> 00:19:32.119
Not that I'm thinking about it.

00:19:32.119 --> 00:19:33.319
There's a lot more going on.

00:19:34.359 --> 00:19:37.160
But yeah, I did learn a couple of things here.

00:19:39.160 --> 00:19:44.040
And that's what I want to leave you with, is that hacking umap and winning the contest,

00:19:44.599 --> 00:19:49.160
runner-up position, wasn't really the point, of course, of this talk, right?

00:19:49.160 --> 00:19:55.560
It's the mindset that you can visualize the behavior of an algorithm, right?

00:19:55.560 --> 00:19:57.719
That this can be a really insightful exercise.

00:19:58.599 --> 00:20:01.319
That's my main take-home message for you.

00:20:01.880 --> 00:20:03.640
And there are various strategies to do so.

00:20:03.640 --> 00:20:06.439
You don't always have to hack an algorithm in order to do this.

00:20:06.439 --> 00:20:09.719
You don't always have to produce an animation, okay?

00:20:11.560 --> 00:20:16.760
And of course, these tools that I've used, umap, Polaris, Plotline, and FFmpeg,

00:20:16.760 --> 00:20:19.640
they're fantastic and also by themselves.

00:20:20.439 --> 00:20:23.479
Oh yeah, and again, I want to stress that in the very end,

00:20:23.479 --> 00:20:26.760
it was the Unix command line that saved the day.

00:20:27.640 --> 00:20:28.359
Thank you very much.

00:20:35.479 --> 00:20:37.400
All right, thank you so much, Jeroen.

00:20:37.400 --> 00:20:39.880
One more time will be stuck in my head for the rest of the day now.

