00:22:37.800 --> 00:22:42.119
I was wondering, since you're very much into different visualizations,

00:22:42.760 --> 00:22:44.520
do you have a favorite library?

00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:46.359
Maybe a favorite library for yourself

00:22:46.359 --> 00:22:48.839
that you like just to do the easy plots,

00:22:48.839 --> 00:22:51.800
and maybe the favorite library of your stakeholders as Xomnia.

00:22:53.400 --> 00:22:58.439
Well, my favorite library, don't be surprised, is plot 9.

00:22:59.719 --> 00:23:00.839
Yes, no, no, no, really.

00:23:01.719 --> 00:23:06.439
This morning in the train, Thijs gave me some CSV with these timings, right?

00:23:06.439 --> 00:23:09.000
You remember the slide where I showed the timings

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:14.119
of the different queries that Polaris was performing

00:23:14.119 --> 00:23:15.880
and different versions of Polaris?

00:23:15.880 --> 00:23:17.319
Thijs gave me the CSV this morning,

00:23:17.319 --> 00:23:21.319
and in the train, I was just hacking my way through this, you know?

00:23:21.319 --> 00:23:26.839
And what I like about plot 9 is that it's based on the grammar of graphics, right?

00:23:26.839 --> 00:23:29.560
So it takes some time to getting used to,

00:23:29.560 --> 00:23:33.239
but once you understand it, it all makes sense.

00:23:33.239 --> 00:23:37.000
And then you rarely have to consult the documentation.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:38.599
I mean, don't get me wrong.

00:23:38.599 --> 00:23:41.640
With Seaborn, right, you can produce nice-looking plots.

00:23:41.640 --> 00:23:44.920
But I personally, I always have to consult the documentation

00:23:44.920 --> 00:23:50.119
on which arguments that function accepts, for example, right?

00:23:50.119 --> 00:23:51.160
And matplotlib, right?

00:23:51.160 --> 00:23:56.280
Well, plot 9 is based on matplotlib, so matplotlib is the OG of plotting,

00:23:56.280 --> 00:23:59.560
and you can do anything you want in matplotlib,

00:23:59.560 --> 00:24:01.880
but it just takes a lot of coding, yeah?

00:24:02.680 --> 00:24:05.319
Altair, great for interactive visualizations.

00:24:06.680 --> 00:24:10.920
Perhaps less so for creating animations or videos, right?

00:24:10.920 --> 00:24:13.319
You would have to, it's browser-based.

00:24:13.319 --> 00:24:20.280
So it's also to say that each data visualization library has its pros and its cons.

00:24:20.280 --> 00:24:24.199
So I've definitely used others in my work, yeah.

00:24:24.199 --> 00:24:26.119
So if you're, like, left on the, you know,

00:24:26.119 --> 00:24:29.880
on an island with one plotting tool, it's going to be plot 9.

00:24:31.160 --> 00:24:32.199
Sorry, say again?

00:24:32.199 --> 00:24:35.239
I was just wondering, so if you're, like, left on the deserted island,

00:24:36.040 --> 00:24:39.319
non-accessible by other plotting libraries with your laptop,

00:24:39.959 --> 00:24:42.199
and just one package is going to be plot 9.

00:24:42.199 --> 00:24:44.439
Exactly, and then I'll survive that island.

00:24:44.439 --> 00:24:46.520
You will survive on plot 9, excellent.

00:24:47.319 --> 00:24:48.920
Who needs food when you have plot 9?

00:24:49.640 --> 00:24:50.599
Other questions?

00:24:52.119 --> 00:24:54.520
Yeah, thank you for your presentation.

00:24:55.400 --> 00:25:02.040
I was just wondering if you could extend plot 9 functionalities,

00:25:02.040 --> 00:25:04.040
like the way you could do in ggplot2,

00:25:04.040 --> 00:25:08.040
because ggplot2 has a very rich ecosystem of packages, themes,

00:25:09.319 --> 00:25:12.599
we have gganimate, ggthemes.

00:25:12.599 --> 00:25:17.959
So how is plot 9 in that regard?

00:25:18.680 --> 00:25:19.079
Thank you.

00:25:19.079 --> 00:25:21.640
Yeah, so the question was, ggplot, right,

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:26.520
the R package has a rich ecosystem of all these plugins.

00:25:27.560 --> 00:25:31.400
Plot 9, unfortunately, doesn't have such a thing just yet.

00:25:31.400 --> 00:25:35.640
And this is all because, well, for the last few years,

00:25:35.719 --> 00:25:40.680
Hassan has been the only person working on this.

00:25:40.680 --> 00:25:45.000
So he's using all his time to create this wonderful package.

00:25:46.119 --> 00:25:49.000
Hopefully, now that Posit has adopted plot 9,

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:55.800
I do hope that soon it will have also the ability to add plugins,

00:25:55.800 --> 00:25:59.400
because I think that's really, really powerful.

00:25:59.400 --> 00:26:04.359
In the same way that Polars has the ability to write plugins for, right?

00:26:04.359 --> 00:26:05.079
Very powerful.

00:26:05.640 --> 00:26:07.479
So not yet, hopefully soon.

